Brief Introduction to: - **Who** am I? - **What** you will learn - **Why** this class matters - **How** things will work ::: ::: ## Lab Instructor {.smaller} ::: columns ::: {.column width="50%"} ![](https://emmarshall.github.io/runza/img/emw-avatar.png) Emma Marshall, JD, MA :e-mail: [Email](emma.marshall@husker.unl.edu) :alarm_clock: Office Hours: [zoom](https://unl.zoom.us/j/6374970867) \| BURN 230 ::: ::: {.column width="50%"} ::: {.body .v-center-container} - Law-Psychology (Joint JD/PhD) Program - Studies legal decision-making - Brank Law & Policy Lab ::: r-stack ![](../images/searches.jpg){.fragment fig-align="center" width="400" height="300"} ![](../images/warrants.png){.fragment fig-align="center" width="250" height="250"} ![](../images/judges.png){.fragment fig-align="center" width="250" height="250"} ::: ::: ::: ::: # What you will learn {background-image="images/fitz.png" background-opacity="0.1"} ## Learning Objectives :dart: {.smaller} ::: v-center-container ::: body - How to... - :mag: **Locate, summarize, critique, & integrate** primary research and research reviews - :thought_balloon: **Propose** original research hypotheses based on your consideration of previous research - :clipboard: **Plan** the procedures & materials for data collection & analysis relevant to research hypotheses - :speech_balloon: **Report** all of the above using a standard (i.e., APA) format and style ::: ::: ## Lab Materials :books: {.smaller} ::: vspace ::: ::: {.body .nonincremental .fragment .fade-in fragment-index="1"} - **Canvas:** Lab section page for links to materials, lectures & assignments - [Zotero](https://www.zotero.org/){preview-link="true"}: APA-citation manager - [SPSS](https://itprocurement.unl.edu/ibm-spss-product-information) or [Jamovi](https://www.jamovi.org/): Data analysis ::: ::: {layout-ncol="3"} ::: {.fragment .fade-in fragment-index="3"} ![SPSS](../images/spss.png){width="260"} ::: ::: {.fragment .fade-in fragment-index="2"} ![Zotero](../images/zotero.png){width="250"} ::: ::: {.fragment .fade-in fragment-index="3"} ![Jamovi](../images/jamovi.png){width="250"} ::: ::: ## SPSS vs. Jamovi ::: {layout-ncol="2"} ::: col ::: {.body .nonincremental}
![SPSS](../images/spss.png){width="150"} [Download](https://itprocurement.unl.edu/ibm-spss-product-information) - Available in Lab - Costs \$\$ - Widely used
::: ::: ::: col ::: {.body .nonincremental}
![Jamovi](../images/jamovi.png){width="150"} [Download](%22https://www.jamovi.org/%22) - Personal only - FREE - Built on R
::: ::: ::: ## Lab Grade (40% total) ::: vspace2 ::: ::: {.columns .v-center-container} ::: {.column width="50%"} ::: {.body .nonincremental} - Lab assignments (20%) - In-Class - Take-Home ::: ::: ::: {.column width="50%"} ::: {.body .nonincremental} - Research project (20%) - Literature Review - APA-Style Report ::: ::: ::: # Questions? {background-image="images/fitz.png" background-opacity="0.2"} # Why is this **lab** required? ## Psych [majors]{.yellow} vs.
Psych [professionals]{.yellow} {.smaller} ![](../images/p-value-statistics-meme.jpg){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="75" height="75"} ::: inner-container ::: {.post-it .nonincremental} The **key** distinction is ability
to **EVALUATE** and **CREATE** new knowledge ::: ::: ::: vspace ::: ::: columns ::: {.column width="50%"}
#### :thought_balloon: **Evaluate** Knowledge ![](../images/line.png){.fragment .fade-up fig-align="center" width="307"}
::: ::: {.column width="50%"}
#### :clipboard: **Create** Knowledge ![](../images/scales.jpeg){.fragment .fade-up fig-align="center" width="307"}
::: ::: ::: notes Possible Question- "Why is this course required???" The fundamental difference between "Psych majors" and "Psych professionals" is the ability to GENERATE and EVALUATE new knowledge To do your job, you'll have to know to find and evaluate knowledge that others have generated! You will sometimes have to generate new knowledge so you can do your job! ::: ## Empirical Research {.smaller .nonincremental} ![](../images/anecdotes.jpg){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="200" height="70"} ::: inner-container ::: {.post-it .nonincremental} - Informs various **real world** decisions & processes - :loudspeaker: Peer-review & replication provide **credibility** - :briefcase: **Not** limited to academic psychology ::: ::: ::: {layout-ncol="3"} ::: {.fragment .fade-in fragment-index="2"} ![](https://emmarshall.github.io/runza/img/icons/find-jobs-on-newspaper-icon.svg){width="215"}
Who does what ::: ::: {.fragment .fade-in fragment-index="3"} ![](https://emmarshall.github.io/runza/img/icons/knowledge-icon.svg){width="175"}
What is known ::: ::: {.fragment .fade-in fragment-index="4"} ![](https://emmarshall.github.io/runza/img/icons/direction-road-sign-icon.svg){width="200"}
How to decide ::: ::: ::: notes The importance of empirical research is that it- - Informs every decision and action by professionals - Every decision and action made by psychological professionals is dependent upon research -- maybe their own, probably someone else's. - In order to be ethical (also legal and bill-able), each diagnosis, treatment choice, evaluation, and decision to stop treatment must be defended in terms of replicated, peer-reviewed, published research. - Not just clinical/treatment decisions but those made within areas of human resources, criminal justice, business, education, engineering, etc. -- all depend on, and use, knowledge acquired by psychological researchers. ::: ## Evaluating Knowledge :thought_balloon: {.smaller} ![](../images/anecdotes.jpg){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="200" height="70"} ### Everyone needs to know how to **understand** & **consume** empirical research... ::: {.columns .v-center-container} ::: {.column width="55%"} ![](../images/example.png) ::: ::: {.column width="45%"} ::: body - **Competent** consumers can: - :mag: **Find** relevant research - :clipboard: **Evaluate (& critique)** research quality (theory, methods, stats) - :dart: **Apply (& integrate)** valuable research information to own work ::: ::: ::: ::: notes While not everyone needs to be a producer of empirical research, every psychological professional needs to be a competent consumer of research. Being a competent consumer of research means being able to ... - locate research that is relevant to your work - critique (evaluate) the quality of the research (theory, methodology, & stats) - integrate the useful information (that passes your evaluation) from the research into your own work What might be some problems with this headline? Not peer reviewed. What about the pandemic might have changed the experiences and testing environment for babies? ::: ## Creating Knowledge :clipboard: {.smaller} ### Many jobs **require** research skills ::: vspace ::: ::: {.columns .v-center-container} ::: {.column width="60%"} ::: vspace ::: ::: body - Funding sources, clients & employers look for: - :bar_chart: Evidence-based decision-making - :hourglass_flowing_sand: Efficiency and cost related concerns - :traffic_light: Competitive advantage ::: ::: ::: {.column width="40%"} ::: vspace ::: ![](../images/business.jpg){fig-align="center" width="300"} ::: ::: ::: notes Most people (not just those in academia) find that they do need to produce research to do their jobs ... Why? Funding sources, clients, & bosses need evidence that what you are doing "works" and is "worth the expense". It is not enough that you "do it better" than the others. You need evidence that what you're doing works, and that it works better than your competitors. This evidence comes from research conducted, analyzed, and reported by you using your own patients/clients. ::: ## Creating Knowledge :clipboard: {.smaller} ### Many jobs **require** research skills ::: vspace ::: ::: {.columns .v-center-container} ::: {.column width="60%"} ::: vspace ::: ::: body - People who understand the research process and can **evaluate**, **integrate**, and **apply** empirical research have: - :money_with_wings: Better job prospects - :trophy: Improved job performance - :bookmark: More flexibility! ::: ::: ::: {.column width="40%"} ![](../images/dogs-with-jobs.jpeg){fig-align="center" width="300"} ::: ::: ::: notes The point is...Research is going to be a more important part of your ongoing professional activities (and your successes) than you may realize. Professionals who better understand the research process and know how to evaluate, integrate, and apply the results from empirical research have greater employment potential do their jobs better! ::: ## Psychology is competitive :cold_sweat: {.smaller} ::: inner-container ::: post-it - Positions often require **advanced** degrees - Grad schools look for stats & methods skills - *Ex: UNL Psych Admissions* ::: ::: ![](../images/lawpsych.png){fig-align="center" width="300"} ::: notes The psychological professions are competitive... for multiple reasons!!! - Many want jobs that "Helping people" is seen by many as an extension of their concerns for individuals and our society, so many want to become psychological professionals Positions for all of these are extremely competitive and required advanced degrees -- and those advanced degree programs are also extremely competitive... For example... Positions for all of these are extremely competitive and required advanced degrees -- some examples, each year ... Our graduate Clinical Psychology Program accepts 10-12 of the 200+ applicants Our Law-Psychology graduate program accepts 4-5 of 60 applicants The Educational Psychology Counseling program takes 6-8 of 100+ And within those programs -- the number of jobs available after also vary by industry and other factors. ::: ## Psychology is competitive! {.smaller} ![](../images/lawpsych.png){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="75" height="75"} ::: inner-container ::: post-it UNL **Clinical** Program accepts
~~10-12 of 200+ applicants~~ ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
Accepted Rejected
``` ::: ::: ## Psychology is competitive! {.smaller} ![](../images/lawpsych.png){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="75" height="75"} ::: inner-container ::: post-it UNL **Law-Psych** Program accepts
~~4-5 of 60 applicants~~ ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
Accepted Rejected
``` ::: ::: ## Psychology is competitive! {.smaller} ![](../images/lawpsych.png){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="75" height="75"} ::: inner-container ::: post-it UNL **Ed Psych** Program accepts
~~6-8 of 100+ applicants~~ ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
Accepted Rejected
``` ::: ::: ## So, what does this mean? {.smaller} ::: inner-container ::: post-it **Research** skills are not only **foundational** but also **iterative**... ::: ::: ::: vspace ::: ::: {.columns .v-center-container} ::: {.column width="40%"} ![](../images/p-value-statistics-meme.jpg){fig-align="center" width="346"} ::: ::: {.column width="60%"} ::: body - Schools (& employers) look for... - :bar_chart: Excellent performance in research methods/stats courses - :thought_balloon: Excellent performance in 400-level courses (writing & critical thinking skills) - :chart_with_upwards_trend: Research experience ::: ::: ::: ::: notes So, we're here to pursue those activities together during your undergraduate "career" to increase your ability to compete for graduate school or a job. What do schools & employers look for ?? Excellent performance in research methods/stats courses Excellent performance in 400-level courses, especially writing and critical thinking skills (which can be improved using the knowledge and skills you'll have an opportunity to learn in here) Research experience (which will be easier to find if you do well in here and have the resultant skills) ::: ## TL;DR ![](https://emmarshall.github.io/runza/img/emw-avatar.png){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="75" height="75"} ::: v-center-container ::: callout-important - Take this course seriously... - ...if you want a good grade. - ...if you want to go to graduate school. - ...if you want a job in [any]{.underline} industry. - ...if you want to understand ... the world! ::: ::: ## Keep in Mind :eyes: ![](https://emmarshall.github.io/runza/img/emw-avatar.png){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="75" height="75"} ::: v-center-container ::: callout-warning - You need a "C" (not a "C-") for this course to count toward the Psychology Major - You **must** complete all exams to receive a passing grade in this course - You **must** complete all the take-home laboratory assignments to receive a passing grade in this class - You **must** attend lab classes to receive a passing grade in this class ::: ::: ## How to Succeed :dart: ![](https://emmarshall.github.io/runza/img/emw-avatar.png){.absolute top="0" right="10" width="75" height="75"} ::: vspace ::: ::: {.columns .v-center-container} ::: {.column width="60%"} ::: vspace2 ::: ::: body - Do the work... - Come to lab... - Be professional... - Embrace the **process**! ::: ::: ::: {.column width="40%"} ![](../images/random.jpg){width="311"} ::: ::: ## <script>
  // htmlwidgets need to know to resize themselves when slides are shown/hidden.
  // Fire the "slideenter" event (handled by htmlwidgets.js) when the current
  // slide changes (different for each slide format).
  (function () {
    // dispatch for htmlwidgets
    function fireSlideEnter() {
      const event = window.document.createEvent("Event");
      event.initEvent("slideenter", true, true);
      window.document.dispatchEvent(event);
    }

    function fireSlideChanged(previousSlide, currentSlide) {
      fireSlideEnter();

      // dispatch for shiny
      if (window.jQuery) {
        if (previousSlide) {
          window.jQuery(previousSlide).trigger("hidden");
        }
        if (currentSlide) {
          window.jQuery(currentSlide).trigger("shown");
        }
      }
    }

    // hookup for slidy
    if (window.w3c_slidy) {
      window.w3c_slidy.add_observer(function (slide_num) {
        // slide_num starts at position 1
        fireSlideChanged(null, w3c_slidy.slides[slide_num - 1]);
      });
    }

  })();
</script>
